  "text": "Molecular flexibility is reflected in the ability of a macromolecule to sample alternative conformations, as for example to open/close the gate of a channel, to mediate the recognition of the receptor or to facilitate the allosteric reactions. Typical examples are centrosomes, which are central regulators of mitosis often amplified in cancer cells. Specifically, the centrosomal protein CEP63 is associated with an aneuploidy and solid tumors in humans. When genetic alterations such as L61P occur, they increase flexibility of the protein, as seen in MD simulations, which was suggested to be the cause of the disease. [CITATION_1] Although mutations may cause different diseases, the common trend is the same, namely, disease can be associated with a change in the conformational or dynamical properties of the corresponding protein (Table 4) .",
